extended_text.content:
After forty years of teaching lithography, Garo Antreasian retired from the University of New Mexico in 1987.  Lacking daily access to a print workshop, Antreasian turned to drawing and painting.

Antreasian's Landfall prints, his first major lithographs in fourteen years, reflected his recent heroically scaled, totemic charcoal drawings and his new canvases inspired by the patterns of sub-Saharan Africa and the Islamic Middle East.
extended_text.title: Gallery Label

58700.title: South of the Serengeti
58700.credit_line: Gift of Garo Z. and Jeanne Antreasian
58700.inscription: inscribed in pencil, L.L.: AP III/V South of the Serengeti | signed an dated in pencil, L.R.: G. Antreasian 2001

extended_text.content:
Antreasian devoted his 45-year career to the pursuit of excellence in color lithography before returning here to the fundamental pleasures of black and white work that had first attracted him in 1940.

"Current trends in prints seem to favor exaggeration in size (very large and very small), the unique impression and the variant edition, a greater physicality of surface, incorporation of multiple media in a single work, recognition once again of the potency of black and white and a more complex admixture of abstraction and figuration."
-Garo Antreasian, 1990
extended_text.title: Gallery Label

58701.title: North of the Niger
58701.credit_line: Gift of Garo Z. and Jeanne Antreasian
58701.inscription: inscribed in pencil, L.L. AP II/V North of the Niger | signed and dated in pencil, L.R.: G. Antreasian 2001

extended_text.content:
In 1965, Antreasian invited Jack Lemon, recently graduated from the Kansas City Art Institute, to come to the University of New Mexico where Antreasian was training lithographers for work at the ground-breaking Tamarind Lithography Workshop.  Lemon returned the favor in 2001 by inviting his mentor to Landfall Press to collaborate on three lithographs.

A fixture in Chicago for 35 years, Jack Lemon and his Landfall Press relocated to Santa Fe, New Mexico in 2005.
